Papadaki’s critique of Kant’s view on sexual objectification often centers on the idea that Kant’s moral framework—rooted in treating people as ends in themselves—may not fully capture the complexities of sexual ethics. She argues that Kant’s focus on humanity as the sole basis for moral evaluation (e.g., in *Metaphysics of Morals*) oversimplifies the nuances of sexual relationships and objectification. Thus, she challenges Kant’s assumption that the "wrong" of objectification is solely tied to dehumanization.
